Moreover the seeds of the alfa- roba, if carelessly scattered in any soil, vwill certainly, and quickly grow up into trees, The white alfaroba affords not only meat, drink, and medicine, but also excellent materials for building waggons, houses- and ships: for its violet-coloured wood is docile, and extremely firm, even under water. The leaves of this tree are small; and from its little pale fiowers grow seeds, inclosed in a pod. They ripen in the month of November, and last in the woods till March, or are gradually collected and pre— served at home by provident persons.

The other species of alfaroba, which the Spa- niards call the black, resembles the former in all respects, except that it is smaller and· sweeter. Its dusky bark is covered with red spots.
